File: Jacob Zuma appears in the Pietermaritzburg High Court on corruption charges in Pietermaritzburg. JOHANNESBURG - Former president, Jacob Zuma's contempt application by the state capture inquiry is headed to the constitutional court on 25 March.
Deputy Chief Justice Raymond Zondo asked for an urgent order to declare Zuma in contempt of court and sentence him to two years in prison if found guilty. WATCH: Gifts roll in for Zuma The former president failed to show up at the commission last month despite summonses and an order from the apex court to do so. The Constitutional Court says Zuma, the police minister and the police commissioner should file answering affidavits by next week Monday.